value.name: Central Park
value.snippet: Central Park is an urban park in New York City located between the Upper West and Upper East Sides of Manhattan. It is the most visited urban park in the United States and one of the most filmed locations in the world.

value.name: Statue of Liberty National Monument
value.snippet: The Statue of Liberty National Monument is a symbol of freedom and democracy, a must-see attraction in New York City, welcoming visitors from around the world.

value.name: Empire State Building
value.snippet: The Empire State Building is a 102-story skyscraper located in Midtown Manhattan, New York City, and is one of the most famous landmarks in the United States.

value.name: Times Square
value.snippet: Times Square is a major commercial intersection, tourist destination, entertainment center, and neighborhood in the Midtown Manhattan section of New York City at the junction of Broadway and Seventh Avenue.

value.name: Brooklyn Bridge
value.snippet: The Brooklyn Bridge is a hybrid cable-stayed/suspension bridge in New York City, connecting the boroughs of Manhattan and Brooklyn by spanning the East River.

value.name: The Metropolitan Museum of Art
value.snippet: The Metropolitan Museum of Art of New York City, colloquially 'the Met', is the largest art museum in the United States.

value.name: Rockefeller Center
value.snippet: Rockefeller Center is a large complex consisting of 19 commercial buildings in Midtown Manhattan, New York City, which was declared a National Historic Landmark in 1987.

value.name: High Line Park
value.snippet: The High Line is a public park built on a historic freight rail line elevated above the streets on Manhattan’s West Side.

value.name: Broadway
value.snippet: Broadway refers to the famous street in Manhattan that has come to represent the pinnacle of live theater and musical performances in New York City.

value.name: 9/11 Memorial & Museum
value.snippet: The National 9/11 Memorial & Museum is a memorial and museum in New York City commemorating the September 11, 2001 attacks, which killed 2,977 people.

queryContext.originalQuery: top 10 tourist attractions in New York City

value.name: Statue of Liberty National Monument
value.snippet: The Statue of Liberty is not only a national monument but also a symbol of freedom and democracy. Guided tours are available, and the pedestal observation deck offers excellent city views.

value.name: Central Park
value.snippet: Central Park offers a respite from the cityscape with its 843 acres of paths, lakes, and lawns. Attractions within the park include the Belvedere Castle, Strawberry Fields, and the Central Park Zoo.

value.name: Empire State Building
value.snippet: One of the most iconic buildings in New York, the Empire State Building features an observatory on the 86th floor giving visitors a panoramic view of the city.

value.name: Times Square
value.snippet: Known as 'The Crossroads of the World', Times Square is famous for its electric billboards, Broadway theaters, and bustling atmosphere.

value.name: The Metropolitan Museum of Art
value.snippet: The Met is one of the world's largest and most prestigious art museums, with an extensive collection that spans thousands of years.

value.name: 9/11 Memorial and Museum
value.snippet: The 9/11 Memorial & Museum commemorates the lives lost during the tragic events of September 11, 2001, and features twin reflecting pools set within the footprints of the original Twin Towers.

value.name: The Museum of Modern Art (MoMA)
value.snippet: MoMA is known for its extraordinary exhibitions and the world's finest collection of modern and contemporary art.

value.name: Brooklyn Bridge
value.snippet: The Brooklyn Bridge offers a magnificent view of the New York skyline and the East River. It's a favorite spot for walking and biking.

value.name: Fifth Avenue
value.snippet: Fifth Avenue is one of the most famous shopping streets in the world, offering high-end boutiques and historic landmarks.

value.name: Broadway
value.snippet: The heart of the American theatre industry, Broadway is home to many of the city’s most significant theaters and musical performances.
